Introduction to programming with C
Why(and why not) to learn C
Why
One of the most popular languages.
Very efficient and fast.
Used everywhere
computers, supercomputers, routers, phone, cars, robots , .
Can program in most languages if you already know C
Very small in size: just 32 keywords
And why not ?
Harder to learn than some languages
Less readable code
About C
Created 1970 by Dennis Ritchie
Successor of language B created at bell labs
C is imperative , procedural , compiled
language
Imperative : commands run one by one
Procedural : made up of functions of different types
Compiled : program converted from C to machine code
before execution.

Perform the operation and print the result
If operation does not exist : print error
Calculator 2 : Full
implementation
{int num1;
int num2;
char operation;
cout << " Provide 2 numbers \n";
cin >> num1;
cin >> num2;
cout << "\n Provide the operation \n";
cin >> operation;
if (operation == '+)
cout << num1 + num2;
else if (operation == '-)
cout << num1 - num2;
else if (operation == '*)
cout << num1 * num2;
else if (operation == '/)
cout << num1 / num2;
elsecout << "Error : not a valid operation";
}
Flowcharts
What are flowcharts for?
agraphical representation of a computer programs
sequence of functions (as distinct from the data it
processes).
Why use flowcharts?
Flowcharts show the relationship between input, processes
and output in a visual form.
Flowcharts
Different symbols
Start/end ->
Arrows shows relationship between shapes
Input/output ->
Process ->
Decision ->
Connector represents the continuation of the flow of the chart, usually
used for charts going over multiple pages ->

Find factorial of a number
Create a function to find a factorial of a number
Read a number from user
Pass the number as function argument

Factorial of a number
1! = 1
2! = 1 x 2
3! = 1 x 2 x 3
4! = 1 x 2 x 3 x 4
You would need to know/learn
How to use a loop ( for loop is good)
